In contrast, the energy density (Wh L−1) of the Li-O2 battery has rarely been discussed and actual cell-scale values have been disregarded in many studies. This may be because the theoretical maximum value of a Li-O2 battery with a lithium anode (i.e., 2,040 Wh L−1) is not much higher than that of a Li-ion battery with a LiCoO2 cathode and carbon anode (1,940 Wh L−1). 18 Especially for transportation applications, a high energy density is desired because of the limited space available in a vehicle. 19 Here, we demonstrate Li-O2 battery cells with complete cell-scale specific energy and energy densities as high as 1,214 Wh kgcell −1 and 896 Wh Lcell −1, respectively, by seamlessly integrating all the best-performing components in a folded structure that allows cells to share their gas-diffusion layers (GDLs) with adjacent cells and eliminate current collectors between the cells. 20 Transport phenomena inside the cell with a Li2O2 passivating film-formation mechanism were also studied, and the optimum performance as well as the capacity-limiting factors of the cell was predicted by mathematical modeling and computer simulations. Briefly, on the macroscopic cell scale, the mismatch of electronic conductivities between the GDL and anode, the depth (D) of the cell, and the thickness of the GDL could cause undesired electric flow and oxygen flux. On the microscopic cathode scale, the porosity (
ϵ l
) of the cathode and the reaction surface area of the carbon in the cathode simultaneously determine cell death mechanisms, for example, through surface passivation and/or clogging. Although models of Li-O2 battery systems have been previously reported, 21 ours is the first to introduce a complete Li-O2 battery cell model that includes the oxygen gas flow generated by the cathode reaction.

Figure 4C shows the changes in the porosity (
ϵ l
) and Li2O2 thickness in 2- and 8-cm cells at various DODs. As cell discharge progresses, the porosity decreases with increased Li2O2 thickness. In the 2-cm-deep cell the changes occur uniformly, whereas in the 8-cm-deep cell the Li2O2 thickness increases from the oxygen inlet side. When the thickness of the Li2O2 reaches about 9 nm, the carbon surfaces are mostly passivated with almost zero surface conductivity (Figure 4D) without pore clogging (corresponding to a porosity higher than 0.44 at 100% DOD). In the 2-cm cell the entire cathode area is utilized, whereas in the 8-cm cell the inner part of the cathode in the cell is still unutilized and conductive, which demonstrates local usage and surface passivation of the cathode even at 100% DOD.
